Comment: I went with the French opening with the King's pawn to e5 and my opponent made the move h6.
Preparatory move I presume I know it is used to defend against the knight landing on g5.
And here it is Nf3.  This move protects h4 and could be a threat to the king if I were able to move onto g5 but this is not possible with pawn at h6.
Black played the French opening, wing gambit and moved e6 getting ready for his next move d5.
So I develop my LB to c4 it covers two diagonals.  I thought that this may stop d5 move but black was not going to let this bishop stop him taking the d5 square.
Black now played d5 which I had not realised was now protected twice by the pawn and the queen.
I thought I should take d5 pawn and no doubt black would reciprocate.
This now left me with a pawn which I could not take since the queen was protecting it.  I should have seen that I would be left with a defended pawn which I would not be able to capture.
So I moved LB back to e2!  All my advantage given away.  I should have moved my LB back to b3 rather than e2 but I thought I was protecting my king.
Black looks better just now.  I have only one piece developed and as white I had the advantage but I lost it.
It seems like I am starting over again.  Now I play c3 ready to play d4.
Black develops his knight to Nf6.
As black played Nf6 I thought I would play d3 to deter  him from moving onto the fourth row with his knights.
Black developed his DB to d6 attacking my h2 pawn and has access to 2 diagonals to a3 and h2.
I play h3 to again stop the f knight coming down to g4.  I can castle but have not done so as I feel I am behind and black may attack at any time.
Black castles.

I have moved Db up to e3 to control 2 diagonals.  I do not have any control of the centre but black also only has one pawn on the 5th row.  But this pawn is in the 4 squares which make up the centre of the board.
Once black castled he moved his rook out to e8 to take control of e file which white currently has 2 bishops and the king is still on its square in the centre.
I pushed pawn to c4 threatening d5.
Black moves pawn to d4 threatening DB on e3.  DB is unable to take as d4 is protected by c6 knight.
